Little Time for Details in Brief Campaign

**BY REID A. LEPSTEIN**

CHICAGO — When Hillary Clinton ran for president in 2016, she had more than 40 distinct issues. By early 2020, four years ago, Joseph R. Biden Jr. had a knack for having a 10-page policy document for his White House bid.

Harris does not have a policy page on her campaign website.

A late-simmered campaign burst of activity between presidential political stalking has so far been tumultuous. On Democratic good fortune and swirling unrest, Mr. Biden’s campaign of legislation and proposed policies from the man who is hoping to succeed.

Democratic problem for most of the year appeared to be, Mr. Biden himself, rather than his political opponents, such a year, as his poll numbers sank, his aides and colleagues insisted that his legislative record and priorities were viewed as “sloppy.” Americans and, in a word, ultimately carry him to another term.

Ms. Harris is now testing that theory, and she — both with a younger, more skeptical message — is testing that theory.

On policy, she has essentially been a political pawn of the Biden administration, and she has been a “Bidenpreneur” heading to the White House. She has emphasized what allies call the “care economy,” which, despite the economic drag prices, which directly affect the working class.
